comment:
The lack of his name in the article is not relevant, because being able to infer who the person is sufficient for defamation especially when she specially dated it as ‚Äú2 years ago‚Äù. And in fact, 3 out of 4 statements Depp‚Äôs suing over have already been upheld as potentially defamatory and actionable. 

Also Heard‚Äôs is currently on her FOURTH attempt to have the ‚Äúmost solid case of evidence‚Äù the ‚Äúprosecutors had ever seen‚Äù üôÑdismissed because of the UK verdict.

This is very unlikely to happen because the motion doesn‚Äôt meet the requirements for dismissal which states that the parties had to be identical, which they weren‚Äôt, and because Heard, as a witness and not a party, didn‚Äôt have to submit discovery so Depp couldn‚Äôt receive a full and fair trial compared to the VA trial.

Regardless of her latest attempts, the UK ruling wouldn‚Äôt have made a difference in the VA case had Depp won or lost, because that would essentially change the jury‚Äôs job. It is the jury‚Äôs job to decide who was the abuser to the civil standard, not whether the UK judge was right. Therefore the ruling is nothing more than an opinion.
